from ieeg.auth import Session
from IPython.display import Image
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from scipy import signal as sig

from google.colab import files

def create_pwd_file(username, password, fname=None):
  if fname is None:
    fname = "{}_ieeglogin.bin".format(username[:3])
  with open(fname, 'wb') as f:
    f.write(password.encode())
  files.download(fname)
  print("-- -- IEEG password file saved -- --\n")

1 Unit Activity (15 pts)¶

The dataset I521 A0001 D001 contains an example of multiunit human iEEG data recorded by Itzhak Fried and colleagues at UCLA using 40 micron platinum-iridium electrodes. Whenever you get new and potentially unfamiliar data, you should always play around with it: plot it, zoom in and out, look at the shape of individual items of interest (here, the spikes). The spikes here will be events appx. 5 ms in duration with amplitudes significantly greater than surrounding background signal.

5b¶

Write a short bit of code to detect the times of each spike peak (i.e., the time of the maximum spike amplitude) within your time-window. Plot an x above each spike peak that you detected superimposed on the plot from Q1.5a. (Hint: find where the slope of the signal changes from positive to negative and the signal is also above threshold.) (5 pts)

In [10]:
#Your code here
i = 0
time_range_list = []
data_list = []

while (i < len(data)):

  ### Threshold: 40, '+' Slope: Prev < Current ; '-' Slope: Next < Current
  if (data[i][0] > 40 and data[i-1][0] < data[i][0]
  and data[i+1][0] < data[i][0]):

    time_range_list.append(time_range[i])
    data_list.append(data[i][0])

  i = i + 1

### Detect the times of each of three spike peaks
print("Time of the 1st spike peak:", time_range_list[0], "seconds")
print("Time of the 2nd spike peak:", time_range_list[1], "seconds")
print("Time of the 3rd spike peak:", time_range_list[2], "seconds\n\n")

plt.scatter(time_range_list, data_list, marker = 'x', color = 'r')
plt.plot(time_range, data)
plt.xlabel('s (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('V (microvolts)')
plt.title("re-plot Q1.5a with 'x' above each spike peak")
plt.show()

j = 0

data_list_new = []

while (j < len(data_new)):

  ### Threshold: 50, '+' Slope: Prev < Current ; '-' Slope: Next < Current
  if (data_new[j][0] > 50 and data_new[j-1][0] < data_new[j][0]
  and data_new[j+1][0] < data_new[j][0]):

    time_range_new_list.append(time_range_new[j])
    data_list_new.append(data_new[j][0])

  j = j + 1

### Detect the times of 32 spike peaks in the entire data sample
print("List includes times of 32 spike peaks:\n", time_range_new_list, "seconds\n\n")

plt.scatter(time_range_new_list, data_list_new, marker = 'x', color = 'r')
plt.plot(time_range_new, data_new)
plt.xlabel('s (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('V (microvolts)')
plt.title("re-plot entire data sample with matplotlibs")
plt.show()

print(len(data_list_new), "Spikes")
